705819f-b.text:
(1)
At the intersection of Myrtle Ave., with Palmetto Street and Wyckoff Ave., showing (center) at the N.E. corner of Myrtle Ave., and Palmetto Street. The 4-story building owned by the Bushwick R.R. Co., had its offices and stables, on land owned by Peter Meserole in 1855. This building was partly destroyed by fire on September 15, 1923. The cafe at the right, is at the S.E. corner of Wyckoff and Myrtle Aves. To the left is a portion of the Myrtle Ave. Elevated line of the B.M.T. (The elevated makes a sharp turn from Myrtle Ave., into Palmetto Street at this point).
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same, showing a closer view of the R.R. Co's building.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)
The same, showing the opposite corner occupied by the Parthenon Theatre. The theatre's site was originally part of the Ganta Farm, which was sold for $4,000 per acre, to the Bushwick R.R. Co., which erected its Ridgewood Depot and stables here in 1872. This corner while in Brooklyn in 1916, is now (1929) in Queens County.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)
The same, showing the R.R. Co's building after the fire.
1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

707458f-b.text:
(1)
Wyckoff Ave., at the S.E. corner of Palmetto Street, showing the car barns of the Brooklyn City R.R. (B.R.T.). The upper stories of the end buildings, were cut down in 1924. (This property from 1855 to 1869, belonged to the Troutman Estate).
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)
The same, another view. (This structure was erected in 1881).
1922
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)  The same, showing the Myrtle Ave. Elevated at the right.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)
The same, showing a closer view of the upper part of the corner building. In the background on the north side of Wyckoff Ave., is
the Zerweck Brewery.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
